'''Nakatomi Itate Shrine''' (なかとみ いたてじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Hyōgo Prefecture|Q130290|qid=Q130290|1=Hyōgo Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Tatsuno City|Q877190|qid=Q877190|1=Tatsuno, Hyōgo}}{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ibo Town|1=UNKNOWN}}{{ill|lt=Ibo Town Nakatomi|UNKNOWN|lt=Nakatomi}}. It is an {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Engishiki shrine|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286|lt=Shikinaisha}}, classified as a {{ill|lt=Myōjin Taisha|Q9610964|qid=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}, a former prefectural shrine, and a former shrine receiving offerings of sacred food and heihaku. Because it is located in the district named Nakatomi (pronounced Nakajin),<ref>The former {{ill|lt=Nishiharima|Q11628288|qid=Q11628288|1=Nishiharima}} region’s {{ill|lt=Isei District|Q11498436|qid=Q11498436|1=Issai district}} Nakatomi Village ({{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Nakajin Village|1=UNKNOWN}}), Nakatomi of {{ill|lt=Ibo Village|Q17193534|qid=Q17193534|1=Ibo}}, later part of {{ill|lt=Tatsuno City|Q2570410|qid=Q2570410|1=Tatsuno}}</ref> it is locally called “Nakajin–Indatsu Shrine,” using the on’yomi reading. It enshrines together the Engishiki-listed '''Awaji Shrine''' through {{ill|lt=enshrinement together|Q11412524|qid=Q11412524|1=Co-Enshrinement}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|qid=Q10881556|lt=Isotakeru-no-Mikoto|1=Isotakeru-no-Mikoto}}
At present, it also enshrines {{ill|qid=Q1502690|lt=Takemikazuchi|Q1502690|qid=Q1502690|lt=Ōkashima-no-Kami|1=Takemikazuchi}} and {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ōkayama-toomi-no-Kami|1=UNKNOWN}}, the deities of the Engishiki Awaji Shrine.

=== History ===
It is traditionally said to have been founded on the 15th day of the 6th month of {{ill|lt=Hōki|Q18520676|qid=Q18520676|1=Hōki}} 1, and it is listed as a {{ill|lt=Myōjin Taisha|Q9610964|qid=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}} in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}. From the medieval period, however, due to {{ill|lt=Ryōbu Shintō|Q4402813|qid=Q4402813|1=Ryobu Shinto}}, ascetic practitioners became involved in shrine affairs and the Twelve Gongen that had been on the mountain behind the shrine were enshrined together in the main shrine. Until the early modern period, the shrine was called {{ill|lt=Zaō Gongen|Q10514059|qid=Q10514059|1=Zaō Gongen}}. On October 10 of Meiji 10, after a formal petition, it reverted to its original name, Nakatomi Itate Shrine. In the same month and year,<ref>Also said to be May of Meiji 12</ref> it was ranked as a prefectural shrine.

=== Chronology ===
: {{ill|lt=Hōki|Q18520676|qid=Q18520676|1=Hōki}} 1 ({{ill|lt=770|Q25021|qid=Q25021|1=770}}) June 15 – Foundation
: {{ill|lt=Daido (Japan)|Q1373191|qid=Q1373191|lt=Daidō|1=Daidō}} 1 ({{ill|lt=806|Q30021|qid=Q30021|1=806}}) – Five households granted as shrine estate to the Nakatomi deity
: {{ill|lt=Shōtoku (Japan)|Q1193848|qid=Q1193848|lt=Shōtoku|1=Shōtoku (era)}} 3 ({{ill|lt=1713|Q6873|qid=Q6873|1=1713}}) March – Construction
: {{ill|lt=Man’en|Q1193862|qid=Q1193862|1=Man'en}} 1 ({{ill|lt=1860|Q7691|qid=Q7691|1=1860}}) – Construction
: {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 10 ({{ill|lt=1877|Q7773|qid=Q7773|1=1877}}) October 10 – Name restored to '''Nakatomi Itate Shrine'''
: Meiji 12 ({{ill|lt=1879|Q7783|qid=Q7783|1=1879}}) May 15 – Ranked as a prefectural shrine
: {{ill|lt=Taishō|Q329174|qid=Q329174|1=Taishō era}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1916|Q2087|qid=Q2087|1=1916}}) April 11 – Designated as a shrine receiving offerings of sacred food and heihaku

