=== The Tsubuoka legend and the Engishiki Tsubuza Amaterasu Shrine ===
The {{ill|lt=Harima no Kuni Fudoki|Q11498726|qid=Q11498726|1=Harima no Kuni Fudoki}} records that the name “Tsubuoka,” the origin of the name Ibo Village in {{ill|lt=Ibo District|Q1042150|qid=Q1042150|1=Ibo District, Hyōgo}}, comes from the story that “when {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|qid=Q276944|lt=Ashihara Shikō-no-Mikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}} came to this mountain to dispute possession of the land with {{ill|lt=Amenohiboko|Q713100|qid=Q713100|lt=Ame-no-Hiboko-no-Mikoto|1=Amenohiboko}} and ate a meal, grains of rice fell.”<ref>Lines 283–288</ref> This Tsubuoka is identified with Mount Nakatomi behind Nakatomi Itate Shrine, and the Engishiki Tsubuza Amaterasu Shrine stands within the precincts.<ref>Sources such as “Jingishi-ryō,” “Harima Kagami,” “Harima Meisho Junran Zue,” and “Ibo District Gazetteer” also suggest a connection between the Engishiki Myōjin Taisha Tsubuza Amaterasu Shrine and the Tsubuoka tradition at the Hachiman Shrine located in Iseyano, Hayashida Village, Ibo District (present-day Kamiiise, Hayashida-chō, Himeji City).</ref>

=== Nakatomi Itate Shrine as a candidate for an Engishiki shrine ===
There are several theories: that this shrine located in Nakajin Village of {{ill|lt=Itō District|Q11498435|qid=Q11498435|1=Ittō district}} (Ibo Town Nakatomi, Tatsuno City) is the Engishiki Nakatomi Itate Shrine; that the Hachiman Shrine on Mount Matsuo in Okusami Village, Itō District (Hachiman, {{ill|lt=Hayashida Town|Q11533214|qid=Q11533214|1=Hayashida}}, {{ill|lt=Himeji City|Q209801|qid=Q209801|1=Himeji}}) is the Engishiki Nakatomi Itate Shrine; and that the {{ill|lt=Uobuki Hachiman Shrine|Q11673954|qid=Q11673954|1=Usuki Hachiman Shrine}} located in Miyauchi Village, Itō District (Miyauchi, {{ill|lt=Aboshi Ward|Q11607184|qid=Q11607184|1=Aboshi}}, Himeji City) is the Engishiki Nakatomi Itate Shrine.

